  <div id="principles">
    <p>The economic principles leading to the creation of value are the same for any organization; whether it be commercial, humanitarian, or political. What may be different are the tools available to measure the value created.</p>

    <p>In our organization, as is true with any organization, we can measure the investment of value in terms of human time and effort expended, and goods and services provided. We can measure the efficiency of our operations as a function of the value provided and the money spent to achieve this value.</p>

    <p>As a humanitarian organization the measurement of return on investment is much more difficult, less precise, and longer term. Our investment of resources is an investment in the future of the people we touch, and the return on this investment is received by the communities they inhabit. We strive to improve their quality of life and the horizons of their dreams and ambitions allowing the value created to be greater than the value invested.</p>

    <p>Our goal is to serve as an efficient vehicle to direct the investment of our donors in a manner that will achieve the maximum return of value in our defined area of interest. That investment is comprised of time, expertise, goods and services, and/or strictly monetary. Our function is to direct, manage, and participate in the placement of that investment to achieve the maximum return to our clients; the women and children of West Africa.</p>

    <p class="quote">Give a person a fish and you feed him for a day. Teach a person to fish and you feed him for a lifetime.</p>

